SIMPLE: press
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Press
<hw>Press</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An
East Indian insectivore (<spn>Tupaia ferruginea</spn>). It is arboreal
in its habits, and has a bushy tail. The fur is soft, and varies from
rusty red to maroon and to brownish black.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Press</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Press
<hw>Press</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Corrupt. fr. <ets>prest</ets>
ready money advanced, a loan; hence, earnest money given soldiers on
entering service. See <er>Prest</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To force
into service, particularly into naval service; to impress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To peaceful peasant to the wars is <qex>pressed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Press</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Press
<hw>Press</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[For <ets>prest</ets>, confused with
<ets>press</ets>.]</ety> <def>A commission to force men into public
service, particularly into the navy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have misused the king's <qex>press</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Press gang</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Pressgang</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a detachment of seamen under the
command of an officer empowered to force men into the naval service. See
<cref>Impress gang</cref>, under <er>Impress</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Press
money</b></col>, <cd>money paid to a man enlisted into public service.
See <cref>Prest money</cref>, under <er>Prest</er>,
<pos>a.</pos></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Press</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Press
<hw>Press</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Pressed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pressing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>presser</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>pressare</ets> to press, fr. <ets>premere</ets>,
<ets>pressum</ets>, to press. Cf. <er>Print</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To urge, or act upon, with force, as weight; to act
upon by pushing or thrusting, in distinction from pulling; to crowd or
compel by a gradual and continued exertion; to bear upon; to squeeze; to
compress; <as>as, we <ex>press</ex> the ground with the feet when we
walk; we <ex>press</ex> the couch on which we repose; we <ex>press</ex>
substances with the hands, fingers, or arms; we are <ex>pressed</ex> in
a crowd.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Good measure, <qex>pressed</qex> down, and shaken together.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke vi. 38.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To squeeze, in order to extract the juice or
contents of; to squeeze out, or express, from something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From sweet kernels <qex>pressed</qex>,⟦br⟧
She tempers dulcet creams.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And I took the grapes, and <qex>pressed</qex> them into Pharaoh's
cup, and I gave the cup into Pharaoh's hand.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xl.
11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To squeeze in or with suitable instruments or
apparatus, in order to compact, make dense, or smooth; <as>as, to
<ex>press</ex> cotton bales, paper, etc.</as>; to smooth by ironing;
<as>as, to <ex>press</ex> clothes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To embrace closely; to hug.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leucothoe shook at these alarms,⟦br⟧
And <qex>pressed</qex> Palemon closer in her arms.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To oppress; to bear hard upon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Press</qex> not a falling man too far.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To straiten; to distress; <as>as, to be
<ex>pressed</ex> with want or hunger</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To exercise very powerful or irresistible influence
upon or over; to constrain; to force; to compel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Paul was <qex>pressed</qex> in the spirit, and testified to the
Jews that Jesus was Christ.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xviii. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To try to force (something upon some one); to urge
or inculcate with earnestness or importunity; to enforce; <as>as, to
<ex>press</ex> divine truth on an audience</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>pressed</qex> a letter upon me within this hour.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be sure to <qex>press</qex> upon him every motive.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To drive with violence; to hurry; to urge on; to ply
hard; <as>as, to <ex>press</ex> a horse in a race</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The posts . . . went cut, being hastened and <qex>pressed</qex>
on, by the king's commandment.</q> <rj><qau>Esther viii.
14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Press</xex> differs from <xex>drive</xex> and
<xex>strike</xex> in usually denoting a slow or continued application of
force; whereas <xex>drive</xex> and <xex>strike</xex> denote a sudden
impulse of force.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pressed brick</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Brick</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Press</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Press
<hw>Press</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To exert pressure; to
bear heavily; to push, crowd, or urge with steady force.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move on with urging and crowding; to make one's
way with violence or effort; to bear onward forcibly; to crowd; to
throng; to encroach.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>pressed</qex> upon him for to touch him.</q>
<rj><qau>Mark iii. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To urge with vehemence or importunity; to exert a
strong or compelling influence; <as>as, an argument <ex>presses</ex>
upon the judgment</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Press</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Press
<hw>Press</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>presse</ets>. See 4th
<er>Press</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An apparatus or machine by which
any substance or body is pressed, squeezed, stamped, or shaped, or by
which an impression of a body is taken; sometimes, the place or building
containing a press or presses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Presses are differently constructed for various purposes
in the arts, their specific uses being commonly designated; <as>as, a
cotton <ex>press</ex>, a wine <ex>press</ex>, a cider <ex>press</ex>, a
copying <ex>press</ex>, etc.</as> See <er>Drill press</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically, a printing press.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The art or business of printing and publishing;
hence, printed publications, taken collectively, more especially
newspapers or the persons employed in writing for them; <as>as, a free
<ex>press</ex> is a blessing, a licentious <ex>press</ex> is a
curse</as>.</def><-- "the press" usually refers to newspaper reporters
-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An upright case or closet for the safe keeping of
articles; <as>as, a clothes <ex>press</ex></as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The act of pressing or thronging forward.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In their throng and <qex>press</qex> to that last hold.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Urgent demands of business or affairs; urgency;
<as>as, a <ex>press</ex> of engagements</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A multitude of individuals crowded together; <?/
crowd of single things; a throng.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They could not come nigh unto him for the <qex>press</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Mark ii. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cylinder press</b></col>, <cd>a printing press in which
the impression is produced by a revolving cylinder under which the form
passes; also, one in which the form of type or plates is curved around a
cylinder, instead of resting on a flat bed.</cd> -- <col><b>Hydrostatic
press</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Hydrostatic</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Liberty of the press</b></col>, <cd>the free right of publishing
books, pamphlets, or papers, without previous restraint or censorship,
subject only to punishment for libelous, seditious, or morally
pernicious matters.</cd> -- <col><b>Press bed</b></col>, <cd>a bed that
may be folded, and inclosed, in a press or closet.</cd>
<au>Boswell.</au> -- <col><b>Press of sail</b></col>,
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>as much sail as the state of the wind will
permit.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pressboard</ent>⟦br⟧
